      <h1 class="blog-title">Inside Legacy Odyssey: A Complete Walkthrough of Every Section</h1>

      <p class="blog-meta">Walkthrough &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 8 min read</p>

      <div class="blog-body">

        <p>Legacy Odyssey is a digital baby book — built as a real website at your child's own .com domain. Your baby gets their name as a website. Parents fill in milestones, photos, and letters through the iOS &amp; Android app. Family visits the book at your-childs-name.com, straight from any browser. Password-protected.</p>

        <p>This post walks through every section of the book and both ways you can edit it.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Two ways to edit</h2>

        <p>You can build your book from the <strong>iOS or Android app</strong>, or from the <strong>web editor</strong> at legacyodyssey.com/account. Both give you access to every section. Use whichever is in front of you — phone when you're at the hospital, laptop when you're at a desk. Changes sync immediately either way.</p>

        <p>The app dashboard shows every section as a grid of cards. Tap any card to open that section's editor. A "Preview" button in the header of each screen jumps straight to how that section looks on your child's website.</p>

        <p>The web editor at <code>/account/book</code> works the same way — a hub listing every section, click any to open the full editor for that section.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 1: Welcome / Child Info</h2>

        <p>The first page visitors see when they open your child's website. It holds:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Your child's first, middle, and last name</li>
          <li>Birth date, birth time, weight, length, birth city, state, and hospital</li>
          <li>A hero photo — the full-width image shown prominently on the Welcome page</li>
          <li>A name meaning note</li>
          <li>A short subtitle (name quote) you write yourself</li>
          <li>A parent quote with attribution</li>
          <li>Per-field toggles for which birth stats to show or hide on the website</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Each birth stat is optional and independently togglable. If you leave weight blank, that tile doesn't appear. Nothing empty shows on the website.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 2: Before You Arrived</h2>

        <p>The pregnancy section, built as a set of cards. Each card has a title, a subtitle, a body, and a photo. Use it for the pregnancy announcement, the ultrasound, the nursery build, the waiting. Add as many cards as you want.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 3: Birth Story</h2>

        <p>Two perspectives, written and displayed separately. Each perspective has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>A <strong>perspective label</strong> — you set this yourself. Defaults to Mom and Dad, but you can type anything: Mama, Papa, Grandma, Partner. Shown on the website as "From ___'s Point of View."</li>
          <li>A <strong>headline</strong> in your own words</li>
          <li>A <strong>full narrative</strong></li>
          <li>A <strong>photo</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <p>There's also a "First Held By" field above both perspectives — for when it wasn't Mom or Dad who held the baby first.</p>

        <p>Fill in one perspective, skip the other — only what you fill in appears on the website.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 4: Your Journey to Us</h2>

        <p>For families whose path to parenthood doesn't follow the standard pregnancy narrative — adoption, surrogacy, foster care, or anything else. It includes:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>A section title and intro</li>
          <li>A story title and main narrative</li>
          <li>A milestone list (label + date pairs, add as many as you want)</li>
          <li>A letter to your child</li>
          <li>A photo gallery</li>
        </ul>

        <p>This section is off by default. Turn it on in Website Sections if it applies to your family.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 5: Coming Home</h2>

        <p>The first days at home, built as a set of cards — up to four. Each card has a title, subtitle, body text, and a photo. Use them for the drive home, the first night, the first visitors, whatever those early days looked like.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 6: Month by Month</h2>

        <p>Twelve months, each as its own entry. Each month has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>A cover photo</li>
          <li>A weight and length check-in</li>
          <li>A highlight (one-line milestone)</li>
          <li>A full note</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The app shows all twelve months as a grid — tap any month to open it. On the website, filled-in months display as a scrollable row of cards. Months with no content stay hidden.</p>

        <p>Most parents fill this section as the year goes on. Add Month 3 this month, come back for the rest later.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 7: Our Family</h2>

        <p>Add the people in your child's life. Default members include Mom, Dad, and four grandparents — you can edit them or add anyone else. Each family member entry has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>A name and relationship role</li>
          <li>A portrait photo</li>
          <li>Two narrative fields</li>
          <li>A quote with attribution</li>
          <li>Four custom label/value metadata pairs</li>
          <li>Three additional album photos with captions</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The detail level here is up to you. Fill in just the basics, or write full bios for everyone.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 8: Your Firsts</h2>

        <p>A running list of milestones. Each entry has an emoji, a title, a date, and an optional note. First smile, first laugh, first word, first steps — add any milestone you want. The list isn't fixed.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 9: Celebrations <em>(paid)</em></h2>

        <p>Birthdays, holidays, and special occasions, organized by year. Each celebration entry has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Title and date</li>
          <li>An eyebrow line (date/place summary)</li>
          <li>A full written account</li>
          <li>Location</li>
          <li>Attendees</li>
          <li>Gifts received</li>
          <li>A photo gallery (unlimited photos with captions)</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Celebrations group by year — "Your First Year," "Year 2," and so on. Each year can hold as many celebrations as you want.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 10: Letters to You <em>(paid)</em></h2>

        <p>Letters written to your child, displayed as actual letter-style cards on the website. Each letter has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>From (who it's from)</li>
          <li>Occasion (when or why it was written)</li>
          <li>Salutation</li>
          <li>Body</li>
          <li>Signature</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Add letters from anyone — Mom, Dad, Grandma, a family friend. There's no limit on the number of letters.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 11: Family Recipes <em>(paid)</em></h2>

        <p>The recipes that belong to your family. Each recipe has a full set of fields:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Title and origin (who it came from)</li>
          <li>A short description and a longer family history</li>
          <li>Prep time, cook time, servings, difficulty</li>
          <li>Ingredients list (amount + item pairs, add as many as needed)</li>
          <li>Step-by-step directions</li>
          <li>Cooking notes</li>
          <li>A photo gallery</li>
        </ul>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 12: Their Keepsakes <em>(paid)</em></h2>

        <p>Items that belong to your child — clothing, toys, gifts, anything worth documenting. Each keepsake entry has:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Title and category</li>
          <li>Age when acquired or given</li>
          <li>Who gave it / where it came from</li>
          <li>A description and a memory or context</li>
          <li>The date it was made or received</li>
          <li>A photo gallery</li>
        </ul>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 13: The Vault <em>(paid)</em></h2>

        <p>Sealed items — letters, messages, and notes intended for your child to read later. Each vault entry has a title, a body, a "sealed by" attribution, and an optional photo. Visitors to the website see the vault is locked but can't open the contents.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Section 14: Website Sections</h2>

        <p>A set of toggles — one per section — that control what appears on the public website. Sections auto-detect whether they have content and show accordingly, but you can override any section manually. Available in both the app and the web editor.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>What family sees: the website</h2>

        <p>When family opens your-childs-name.com, they see a full book-style website. No app to download. No account to create. Just the URL and the password you give them.</p>

        <p>The left-side navigation links to every section with content. The design is consistent throughout — warm cream background, gold accents. Each section is its own page. The website updates in real time as you fill things in.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Your domain: what happens after you buy</h2>

        <p>At checkout you choose your child's domain name and we register it automatically. But there's a short window — usually around 15 minutes — where the domain isn't accessible yet. This is normal: new DNS records need time to spread across the internet's global servers before visitors can reach your site.</p>

        <p>You don't need to wait. The app and the web editor work immediately after purchase. Start filling in your child's book right away. Legacy Odyssey checks your domain automatically every 5 minutes in the background, and the moment your site is confirmed live, you'll receive a <strong>"Your site is live!"</strong> email with your URL and book password ready to share.</p>

        <div class="blog-cta-box">
          <p><strong>Your child's own .com, their own book.</strong></p>
          <a href="https://legacyodyssey.com" class="btn-primary">Get Started &rarr;</a>
        </div>

        <p class="blog-footer-note"><em>Legacy Odyssey is a digital baby book platform. Every family gets their own private .com, unlimited photo storage, and a Time Vault to seal letters until the day you choose. <a href="https://legacyodyssey.com">Start your baby's site today &rarr;</a></em></p>

